      <hedline>
        <hl1>Harm to Public Lands</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from botanist Noel H Holmgren criticizes Clinton administration proposal on national forests for not banning use of off-road vehicles (May 9 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You report that the Clinton administration proposes to ban road building in about a quarter of national forest land but would not ban off-road vehicles (news article, May 9). The use of all-terrain vehicles is one of the most obnoxious things human beings have learned.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You report that the Clinton administration proposes to ban road building in about a quarter of national forest land but would not ban off-road vehicles (news article, May 9). The use of all-terrain vehicles is one of the most obnoxious things human beings have learned.</p>
        <p>We can stand upwind of smokers or paint over graffiti, but there is no way for plants and animals in the roadless areas of public lands to escape the destruction of this mindless pastime.</p>
        <p>I have been doing botanical research in the intermountain West for 36 years and have seen the damage escalate alarmingly. We should make every effort to protect the lands that remain.</p>
        <p>NOEL H. HOLMGREN  Bronx, May 9, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a curator of botany at the New York Botanical Garden.</p>
      </block>
